# The `flt256` Type (Octuple Precision Floating Point)

**Category**: Types → Floating Point → Extended Precision (Extreme)  
**Syntax**: `flt256` (alias: `f256`)  
**Purpose**: 256-bit octuple-precision floating point for specialized scientific computing  
**First Available**: Aria v0.0.1  
**Status**: ✅ Fully implemented (software emulation only)  
**Warning**: ⚠️ **VERY SLOW** - use only when flt128 insufficient!

---

## Overview

`flt256` is Aria's **octuple-precision floating-point type**, providing approximately **70 decimal digits** of precision. This is an **extreme precision** type intended for specialized scientific computing where even flt128's 34 digits are insufficient.

**Key Characteristics**:
- **256 bits** (32 bytes): 1 sign + 19 exponent + 236 mantissa bits
- **~70 decimal digits** of precision (vs flt128's ~34, double's ~15)
- **Range**: ±10⁷⁸⁹¹³ (incomprehensibly massive!)
- **Deterministic**: Bit-exact results across platforms
- **Software emulation**: No hardware support anywhere
- **~100-500× slower** than `double` (possibly slower!)

**Alias**: `f256`

**When to use flt256**:
- ✅ Extreme numerical analysis requiring >34 digits
- ✅ Mathematical research (number theory, chaos theory)
- ✅ Specialized quantum simulations with extreme precision needs
- ✅ Validating numerical algorithms at extreme precision
- ✅ **VERY RARE** - almost never needed in practice

**When NOT to use flt256**:
- ❌ 99.9% of applications (use double, flt128, or exact types instead)
- ❌ Any real-time application whatsoever
- ❌ Production code (too slow, too much memory)
- ❌ Financial calculations (use `fix256` for EXACT decimals)
- ❌ If you're not sure you need it (you probably don't!)

---

## Specifications

| Aspect | flt256 | flt128 | double | float |
|--------|--------|--------|--------|-------|
| **Size** | 32 bytes | 16 bytes | 8 bytes | 4 bytes |
| **Precision** | ~70 digits | ~34 digits | ~15 digits | ~7 digits |
| **Range** | ±10⁷⁸⁹¹³ | ±10⁴⁹³² | ±10³⁰⁸ | ±10³⁸ |
| **Epsilon** | ~10⁻⁷⁰ | ~10⁻³⁴ | ~10⁻¹⁶ | ~10⁻⁷ |
| **Speed** | 100-500× slow | 50-100× slow | 1× | 2× (SIMD) |
| **Hardware** | ❌ None | ❌ None | ✅ Native | ✅ Native |
| **Deterministic** | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ❌ Varies | ❌ Varies |
| **Practical use** | Extremely rare | Rare | Common | Common |

